  "prompt": "Which raw materials are needed for photosynthesis?",
  "response": "Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants, algae, and some bacteria convert light energy into chemical energy, producing oxygen and organic compounds. The raw materials required for photosynthesis are:\n\n1. **Carbon Dioxide (CO\u2082)**: Plants absorb carbon dioxide from the atmosphere through tiny pores called stomata, primarily located on the underside of leaves.\n\n2. **Water (H\u2082O)**: Water is absorbed by the plant's roots from the soil and transported to the leaves through the xylem.\n\n3. **Sunlight**: Light energy from the sun is captured by chlorophyll, the green pigment in the chloroplasts of plant cells.\n\nThese raw materials are used in the following chemical equation for photosynthesis:\n\n\\[ \\text{6CO}_2 + \\text{6H}_2\\text{O} + \\text{light energy} \\rightarrow \\text{C}_6\\text{H}_{12}\\text{O}_6 + \\text{6O}_2 \\]\n\nIn this process, carbon dioxide and water are converted into glucose (a simple sugar) and oxygen, with sunlight providing the necessary energy.",
